  "suggestion": "[learning-theory+clinical-psychology+dynamical-systems+Pavlov-1927+Foa-Kozak-1986] REFINEMENT — Directed History Modulation: Habituation vs. Sensitization. Currently historyMod = 1 + historyLen × 0.3 deepens ALL attractor basins uniformly regardless of what happened in history. This is wrong: repeated safe/gain exposures cause habituation (shallow basins, reduced reactivity), while repeated threat/loss exposures cause sensitization (deep basins, hyperreactivity). Fix: scan history for threat keywords (existing ALLOSTATIC_THREAT_KEYWORDS) vs gain keywords (reward, success, praise, connection). Compute threatRatio = threatCount / historyLen and gainRatio = gainCount / historyLen. Replace historyMod with directional formula: for approach/explore attractors: depth *= (1 - gainRatio * 0.4) [habituation reduces re-approach need]; for avoidance/rumination attractors: depth *= (1 + threatRatio * 1.5) [sensitization deepens threat basins]. Falls out of Pavlov habituation curve (1927) and Foa & Kozak (1986) emotional processing theory. One formula, no new parameters. — Math: For each attractor a: if a.name ∈ {approach, explore, seek-reward, pursue-goal}: depth *= max(0.4, 1 - gainRatio × 0.4); if a.name ∈ {avoidance, rumination, hypervigilance, freeze}: depth *= (1 + threatRatio × 1.5). threatRatio = |{h: h contains threat keyword}| / max(1, history.length). This replaces uniform historyMod = 1 + historyLen × 0.3 which inflates ALL basins.; [social-psychology+interpersonal-theory+Leary-1957+Kiesler-1983+geometry] IMPLEMENT NOW — Interpersonal Circumplex Complementarity Gate (Leary 1957, Kiesler 1983). Social domain predictions currently use ad-hoc string matching (does desc include 'authority'? 'conform'?). Replace with one geometric principle: map person and stimulus to the 2D interpersonal circumplex (dominance × affiliation). The complementarity law: dominant stimulus → submissive response (negate dominance axis); same-side affiliation (friendly elicits friendly, hostile elicits hostile). person_dominance = extraversion - agreeableness (Big5 derivation). stimulus_dominance = +1 if authority/command/order/boss cues, -1 if plea/request/help. stimulus_affiliation = +1 if warmth/praise/friendly, -1 if criticism/hostile/cold. response_dominance = -stimulus_dominance × 0.7 + person_dominance × 0.3. response_affiliation = stimulus_affiliation × 0.8. Map response vector to attractor: high dominance+affiliation → assert; low dominance+high affiliation → conform; low dominance+low affiliation → withdraw. One formula replaces 5 if-branches and handles authority compliance, bystander effect, aggression-reciprocity, and social support simultaneously. — Math: dominance_p = clamp(extraversion - agreeableness, -1, 1). affiliation_p = agreeableness × 2 - 1. For stimulus: dominance_s = keywords_to_dominance_score(desc). affiliation_s = keywords_to_affiliation_score(desc). response_d = -dominance_s × 0.7 + dominance_p × 0.3. response_a = affiliation_s × 0.8 + affiliation_p × 0.2. Map (response_d, response_a) to attractor via nearest neighbor on circumplex quadrants: (+d,+a)→assert, (-d,+a)→conform, (-d,-a)→withdraw, (+d,-a)→compete.; [topology+catastrophe-theory+dynamical-systems+clinical-psychology+Zeeman-1977] NEW — Cusp Catastrophe for Threshold Collapse (Zeeman 1977). The model predicts graded responses across all stress levels. But humans don't break gradually — they snap. A soldier functions under mounting pressure then suddenly freezes. A relationship is strained for months then suddenly ends. 'The last straw' is structurally real. Zeeman's cusp catastrophe from topology explains this: two control parameters (a = chronic load/vulnerability, b = acute perturbation/intensity) produce a folded manifold with two stable equilibrium sheets. Within the cusp region (4a³ + 27b² < 0), the system has two attractors with a forbidden middle zone — transitions are discontinuous, hysteretic. Apply: compute a = allostaticLoad - 0.5 (centered), b = stimulusIntensity - 0.5. If in cusp region (a < 0 and 4a³ + 27b² < 0): predict discontinuous jump — behavior snaps to the opposite extreme of current emotional state (calm → panic, engaged → shutdown). This adds one conditional, explains sudden-onset anxiety, breakdown, flooding, and the hysteresis of recovery (why healing isn't the reverse of breakdown). No new parameters — reuses existing load and intensity. — Math: a = allostaticLoad - 0.5; b = stimulusIntensity × stimulus.personalRelevance - 0.5. cusp_discriminant = 4 × a³ + 27 × b². In cusp zone: a < 0 AND cusp_discriminant < 0 → catastrophic_snap = true. If snap: override attractor selection to deepest-opposite-valence basin (from positive emotional state → deepest negative-valence attractor, and vice versa). Confidence *= 0.85 (model acknowledges hysteresis uncertainty). Explains: sudden depression onset, panic attacks, emotional flooding, abrupt relationship dissolution.",
